{{coi|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox software | name = Thonny | logo = Thonny logo.png | screenshot = Thonny2_0_screenshot_windows_10.png | developer = Aivar Annamaa and contributors | latest_release_version = 3.0.8 | latest_release_date = {{Start date and age|2018|11|16}} | programming_language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]] | operating_system = [[Cross-platform]] | platform = [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[macOS]] | genre = [[Integrated development environment]] | license = [[MIT License|MIT]] | website = {{URL|https://thonny.org}} }}
'''Thonny''' is an [[integrated development environment]] for [[Python (programming language)|Python]] that is designed for beginners. It supports different ways of stepping through the code, step-by-step expression evaluation, detailed visualization of the call stack and a mode for explaining the concepts of references and heap.<ref name="koli">{{cite conference |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2828969 |title=Introducing Thonny, a Python IDE for learning programming |last=Annamaa |first=Aivar |date=2015 |publisher=ACM |book-title=Proceedings of the 15th Koli Calling Conference on Computing Education Research |pages=117-121 |location=Koli, Finland}}</ref>
== Features == *[[Line numbers]] *Statement stepping without breakpoints *Live variables during debugging *Stepping through evaluation of the expressions (expressions get replaced by their values) *Separate windows for executing function calls (for explaining local variables and call stack) *Variables and memory can be explained either by using simplified model (name → value) or by using more realistic model (name → address/id → value) *Simple [[Pip (package manager)|pip]] GUI *Possibility to log user actions for replaying or analyzing the programming process <ref name="iticse">{{cite conference |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2729094.2754849 |title=Thonny, a Python IDE for learning programming |last=Annamaa |first=Aivar |date=2015 |publisher=ACM |book-title=Proceedings of the 2015 ACM Conference on Innovation and Technology in Computer Science Education |pages=343-343 |location=Vilnius, Lithuania}}</ref><ref name="website">{{cite web |url=https://thonny.org |title=Thonny website |access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="magpi">{{cite web |url=https://www.raspberrypi.org/magpi/thonny/ |website=The MagPi Magazine |title=Thonny on a Raspberry Pi: Using the new Python IDE in Raspbian |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="fedoramag">{{cite web |url=https://fedoramagazine.org/learn-code-thonny-python-ide-beginners/ |website=Fedora Magazine |title=Learn to code with Thonny — a Python IDE for beginners |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>
== Availability == The program works on Windows, macOS and Linux. It is available as binary bundle including recent Python interpreter<ref name="website"/> or [[Pip_(package_manager)|pip]]-installable package<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pypi.org/project/thonny/ |website=Python Package Index |title=Thonny Python distribution |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>. It can be installed via operating-system package manager on Debian, Raspberry Pi, Ubuntu and Fedora.
== Reception == Thonny has received favorable reviews from Python and computer science education communities<ref name="jaxenter">{{cite web |url=https://jaxenter.com/thonny-python-ide-150984.html |website=JAXenter |title=Are you a Python newbie? Meet the IDE for beginners |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="cestlaz">{{cite web |url=https://cestlaz.github.io/posts/new-tool-thonny/ |website=C'est la Z |title=New Term New Tool - Thonny, a Python IDE |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="projectcodeed">{{cite web |url=http://projectcodeed.blogspot.com/2018/02/python-ides-for-beginners-thonny-geany.html |website=ProjectCodeEd |title=Python IDEs for beginners - Thonny, Geany or Idle |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>. It has been recommended tool in several programming [[Massive_open_online_course|MOOCs]]<ref name="ricemooc">{{cite web |url=https://www.coursera.org/lecture/python-visualization/installing-packages-in-thonny-aX4ea |website=Python Data Visualization MOOC by Rice University |title=Installing Packages in Thonny |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref name="utmoocs">{{cite web |url=https://courses.cs.ut.ee/2018/eprogalused/fall/Main/Thonny |website=Programmming MOOC by University of Tartu |title=Thonny |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>. Since June 2017 it has been included by default in the [[Raspberry_Pi|Raspberry Pi]]'s official operating system distribution [[Raspbian]]<ref name="raspdefault">{{cite web |url=https://www.raspberrypi.org/blog/a-raspbian-desktop-update-with-some-new-programming-tools/ |website=Raspberry Pi blog |title=A Raspbian desktop update with some new programming tools |accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>.
