{{Starbox begin |name=UDF 2457 }} {{Starbox image | image = [[File:UDF2457-mdwarf-star.jpg|250px|alt=UDF 2457]] | caption = [[Red dwarf]] star UDF 2457 as seen by the [[Hubble Ultra Deep Field]] (UDF) | credit = [[Space Telescope Science Institute|STScI]], [[NASA]], [[European Space Agency|ESA]] }} {{Starbox observe |epoch=J2000 |ra={{RA|03|32|38.79}}<ref name=Wikisky>{{cite web |title=UDF 2457 |publisher=[[Wikisky]] |url=http://www.wikisky.org/?ra=3.5441034&de=-27.80278&zoom=15&show_grid=1&show_constellation_lines=1&show_constellation_boundaries=1&show_const_names=1&show_galaxies=1&show_box=1&box_ra=3.5441034&box_de=-27.80278&box_width=50&box_height=50&img_source=IMG_all |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> |dec={{DEC|-27|48|10.0}}<ref name=Wikisky/> |appmag_v=25<ref name=Wikisky/> |constell=[[Fornax]]<ref name=Wikisky/> }} {{Starbox character |class=[[M dwarf]]<ref name=Malhotra>{{cite web |title=As far as the Hubble can see |author=Sangeeta Malhotra |publisher=[[Arizona State University]] |url=http://malhotra.asu.edu/Welcome_files/ASY-HI1105.pdf |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> |b-v= |u-b= |variable= }} {{Starbox astrometry |radial_v= |prop_mo_ra= |prop_mo_dec= |parallax= |p_error= |absmag_v= |dist_pc= |dist_ly=59,000<ref name=Malhotra/> }} {{Starbox detail |mass= |radius= |luminosity= |temperature= |metal= |rotation= |age= }} {{Starbox reference |Simbad=UDF+2457 }} {{Starbox image | image = [[File:Hubble ultra deep field high rez edit1.jpg|250px|upright=1.0|alt=HUDF]] | caption = UDF 2457 is located above the [[spiral galaxy]] [[UDF 423]] in the lower right quadrant of the Hubble Ultra Deep Field. | credit = }} {{Starbox end}}
'''UDF 2457''' is the [[Hubble Ultra Deep Field]] (UDF) identifier for a [[red dwarf]] [[star]] calculated to be about {{convert|59000|ly|kpc|abbr=off|lk=on}} from Earth<ref name=Malhotra/> with a very dim [[apparent magnitude]] of 25.<ref name=Wikisky/>
The [[Milky Way]] galaxy is about 100,000 [[light-year]]s in diameter,<ref name="ask-astro">{{cite web |date=1998-03-17 |last=Christian |first=Eric |last2=Safi-Harbr |first2=Samar |publisher=NASA: Ask an Astrophysicist |title=How large is the Milky Way? |url=http://imagine.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/ask_astro/answers/980317b.html |accessdate=2007-11-28}}</ref> and the [[Sun]] is about 25,000 light-years from the [[galactic center]].<ref name=gillessenetal2009>{{cite journal |last=Gillessen |first=S. |author2=Eisenhauer |author3=Trippe |author4=Alexander |author5=Genzel |author6=Martins |author7= Ott |title=Monitoring Stellar Orbits Around the Massive Black Hole in the Galactic Center |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=692 |issue=2 |pages=1075–1109 |date=2009 |doi=10.1088/0004-637X/692/2/1075 |arxiv=0810.4674 |bibcode=2009ApJ...692.1075G}}</ref> The small common star UDF 2457 may be one of the farthest known stars inside the main body of the Milky Way. [[Globular cluster]]s (such as [[Messier 54]] and [[NGC 2419]]) and [[List of stellar streams|stellar streams]] are located further out in the [[galactic halo]]{{Update inline|reason=Does location of Messier 54 still hold? Now considered extragalactic?|?=yes|date=April 2017}}.
